That goes along what I found out in the meantime. 
I was able to reduce it down to

```
s1 := "tester"
s2 := "mysessionid"
s3 := "FRENCH"
request = &S4P.GetTranslationData{
    Base_: &S4P.ApiRequest{
        RequestID: &s1,
        SessionID: &s2,
    },
    Language: &s3,
    ResIDs: &S4P.StringArray{
        "Mist",
    },
}
```

which, altough slightly more concise, still seems quite equivalent to the "ugly" sample at http://play.golang.org/p/wDJT7GtGRX - not only that the s1-s3 vars are adding a lot of noise to the code, the variables are also initialized in an somewhat illogical order, because you have to set s1-s3 first, before the rest of the struct can be filled.

Bottom line: I personally think, adding the helpers to the library is a good idea. It would reduce the above code down to something which is closer to what I would call readable and maintainable:

```
request = &S4P.GetTranslationData{
    Base_: &S4P.ApiRequest{
        RequestID: String("tester"),
        SessionID: String("mysessionid"),
    },
    Language: String("FRENCH"),
    ResIDs: &S4P.StringArray{
        "Mist",
    },
}
```

